  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Addressing Immediate Humanitarian Needs of the Most Vulnerable Populations in Ukraine</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">On 24 February 2022, a broad military offensive caused rapid deterioration of the security situation across Ukraine. The intense hostilities, both along the Line of Contact and new areas throughout Ukraine, including Kyiv, have resulted in the loss of lives, injuries, damages to civilian and public infrastructure, and mass displacement of the population throughout the country and to the neighbouring countries. According to the 2022 UN Flash Appeal for Ukraine, 18 million people are projected to be affected, including up to 6.7 million people anticipated to be newly internally displaced. Of the affected population, 12 million people are expected to need urgent humanitarian assistance. Instances of sexual assault and disappearances are also being reported. Through this intervention, IOM aims to provide lifesaving assistance through non-food items, addressing emergency shelter needs, namely damage caused by shelling, and humanitarian transportation support/protection assistance for the affected population in Ukraine. The project is specifically targeting the most vulnerable population affected by the ongoing hostilities, particularly women, children, older persons and persons living with disabilities and/or chronic diseases.</narrative>
  </description>
